nului-2000.html|archivedate=January 22, 2005}}</ref>\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|South Korea International Singles ([[Gaon Chart|Gaon]])<ref name=\"SouthKoreaDebut2\">{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/online/download/list.gaon |title=South Korea Gaon International Chart (Week: January 22, 2012 to January 28, 2012) |publisher=[[Gaon Chart]] |date=December 15, 2012 |accessdate=December 21, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121219094524/http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/online/download/list.gaon |archivedate=December 19, 2012 }}</ref>\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 57\n|-\n{{singlechart|Scotland|5|artist=Britney Spears|song=Lucky|date=20000826|refname=scotland|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Spain|12|artist=Britney Spears|song=Lucky|accessdate=2011-04-02}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Sweden|1|artist=Britney Spears|song=Lucky|accessdate=April 4, 2011|refname=swedenchart}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Switzerland|1|artist=Britney Spears|song=Lucky|accessdate=April 4, 2011|refname=swisschart}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|5|date=20000826|accessdate=November 15, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKindie|1|date=20000826|accessdate=November 15, 2018}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|23|artist=Britney Spears|accessdate=April 4, 2011}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardpopsongs|9|artist=Britney Spears|accessdate=April 4, 2011}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrhythmic|14|artist=Britney Spears|accessdate=April 4, 2011}}\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (2000)\n!Position\n|-\n| Australia (ARIA)<ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-end-of-year-charts-top-100-singles-2000.htm| title=ARIA Annual Chart|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|accessdate =2011-01-09}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|29\n|-\n| Austria (\u00d63 Austria Top 40)<ref>{{cite web | title=Jahreshitparade | publisher=Hung Medien  | url=http://www.austriancharts.at/2000_single.asp | accessdate=2010-08-08 }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|9\n|-\n| Belgium (Ultratop Flanders)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultratop.be/nl/annual.asp?year=2000|title=Jaaroverzichten 2000|publisher=Ultratop|accessdate=February 3, 2020}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|49\n|-\n| Belgium (Ultratop Wallonia)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultratop.be/fr/annual.asp?year=2000|title=Rapports Annuels 2000|publisher=Ultratop|accessdate=February 3, 2020}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|55\n|-\n| Europe (Eurochart Hot 100)<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/UK/Music-and-Media/00s/2000/MM-2000-12-23.pdf|title=Year in Focus \u2013 Eurochart Hot 100 Singles 2000|magazine=[[Music & Media]]|volume=17|issue=52|page=9|date=December 23, 2000|access-date=February 8, 2020}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|23\n|-\n| France (SNEP)<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Disque en France. [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]] |title=Classement Singles - 2000 |url=http://www.disqueenfrance.com/fr/pag-259376-Classements-Annuels.html?year=2000 |accessdate=2010-08-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5yMJQdkSH?url=http://www.disqueenfrance.com/fr/pag-259376-Classements-Annuels.html?year=2000 |archivedate=2011-05-01 }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|100\n|-\n| Germany (Official German Charts)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/charts/single-jahr/for-date-2000 |title=Top 100 Jahrescharts 2000|language=German |work=[[GfK Entertainment]] |publisher=offiziellecharts.de |accessdate=February 27, 2017}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|10\n|-\n| Iceland (\u00cdslenski Listinn Topp 40)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timarit.is/page/3010431?iabr=on#page/n9/mode/2up|title=\u00cdslenski Listinn Topp 100|work=[[DV (newspaper)|Dagbla\u00f0i\u00f0 V\u00edsir]]|language=Icelandic|page=10|date=January 5, 2001|access-date=February 8, 2020}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|34\n|-\n| Netherlands (Dutch Top 40)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.top40.nl/bijzondere-lijsten/top-100-jaaroverzichten/2000|title=Top 100-Jaaroverzicht van 2000|publisher=Dutch Top 40|accessdate=February 3, 2020}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|67\n|-\n| Netherlands (Single Top 100)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dutchcharts.nl/jaaroverzichten.asp?year=2000&cat=s|title=Jaaroverzichten \u2013 Single 2000|website=dutchcharts.nl|accessdate=February 3, 2020}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|41\n|-\n| New Zealand (Recorded Music NZ)<ref>{{cite web|title=New Zealand 2000 - Annual Chart |publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand]] |url=http://www.rianz.org.nz/rianz/chart_annual.asp |accessdate=2010-08-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5r7HjO3zL?url=http://www.rianz.org.nz/rianz/chart_annual.asp |archivedate=2010-07-10 }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|35\n|-\n| Romania (Romanian Top 100)<ref name=\"rt100\"/>\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|13\n|-\n| Sweden (Sverigetopplistan)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sverigetopplistan.se/chart/43?dspy=2000&dspp=1|title=\u00c5rslista Singlar \u2013 \u00c5r 2000|publisher=Sverigetopplistan|language=Swedish|accessdate=February 3, 2020}}</ref>\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|8\n|-\n| Switzerland (Schweizer Hitparade)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hitparade.ch/charts/jahreshitparade/2000|title=Schweizer Jahreshitparade 2000|website=hitparade.ch|accessdate=February 3, 2020}}</ref>\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|25\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{certification Table Top}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=single|region=Australia|artist=Britney Spears|title=Lucky|award=Platinum|certyear=2000|relyear=2000|recent=false|certref=<ref name=auscert>{{cite web | publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]] | title=ARIA Charts - Acreeditations Singles of 2000 | year=2000 | url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-accreditations-singles-2000.htm | access-date=June 25, 2009}}</ref>}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=single|region=Austria|artist=Britney Spears|title=Lucky|award=Gold|certyear=2000|relyear=2000|recent=false|certref=<ref>{{cite web|author=International Federation of the Phonographic Industry |publisher=IFPI (Austria) |title=Gold & Platin (Searchable Database) |date=21 September 2000 |url=http://www.ifpi.at/?section=goldplatin |access-date=8 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130701062753/http://www.ifpi.at/?section=goldplatin |archivedate=1 July 2013 }}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Entry |region=Belgium |type=single |award=Gold |artist=Britney Spears|title=Lucky|relyear=2001|certyear=2000}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=single|region=France|artist=Britney Spears|title=Lucky|award=Silver|certyear=2001|relyear=2000|recent=false|certref=<ref name=fracert>{{cite web|url=http://www.disqueenfrance.com/fr/page-259165.xml?year=2001&type=6 |title=Certifications Singles Argent - ann\u00e9e 2001 |publisher=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]] |access-date=2010-10-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120728203539/http://www.disqueenfrance.com/fr/page-259165.xml?year=2001&type=6 |archivedate=2012-07-28 }}</ref>}} <ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.snepmusique.com/les-disques-dor/page/2/?awards_cat=64&awards_awd=0&awards_year=2001&awards_artist&awards_title&awards_edit_distrib&awards_sort=date_certif-desc&awards_nb=30&submitAdvanced=Rechercher |title = Les Certifications|date = November 2013}}</ref>\n{{certification Table Entry|type=single|region=Germany|artist=Britney Spears|title=Lucky|award=Gold|certyear=2000|relyear=2000|recent=false|certref=<ref name=gercert>{{cite certification|artist=Britney Spears|region=Germany|access-date=2010-08-24}}</ref>}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=single|region=New Zealand|artist=Britney Spears|title=Lucky|award=Platinum|certyear=2000|relyear=2000|recent=false|certref=<ref name=nzcert>{{cite web|url=http://www.rianz.org.nz/rianz/chart.asp |title=Britney Spears Lucky \u2013 New Zealand Certification \u2013 Searchable Database |publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand]] |access-date=2011-04-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090215053322/http://rianz.org.nz/rianz/chart.asp |archivedate=2009-02-15 }}</ref>}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=single|region=Sweden|artist=Britney Spears|title=Lucky|award=Platinum|certyear=2000|relyear=2000|recent=false|certref=<ref>{{cite web | publisher=[[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry]] | title=Certifications - Search for Britney Spears Lucky | year=2000 | url=http://www.hitlistan.se/ | access-date=2012-04-01 }}</ref>}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=single|region=United Kingdom|artist=Britney Spears|title=Born to Make You Happy|award=Silver|certyear=2000|relyear=2000|recent=false|certref=<ref name=ukcert>{{cite web|publisher=British Phonographic Industry |title=BPI Certified Awards (Searchable Database) |url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx |access-date=2010-08-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090924015932/http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx |archivedate=2009-09-24 }}</ref>}}\n|-\n{{Certification Table Bottom|format=3col}}\n\n== Release history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Country\n! Date\n! Format\n! Label\n|-\n\n! scope=\"row\"| Austria\n| rowspan=\"3\"| August 8, 2000<ref name=amazonde>{{cite web|title=Lucky [Single, Maxi] by Britney Spears|url=https://www.amazon.de/Lucky-Britney-Spears/dp/B00004WZPW|website=[[Amazon.com|Amazon.de]]|accessdate=July 5, 2014}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"5\"| [[CD single]]\n| rowspan=\"5\"| [[Jive Records]]\n|-\n\n! scope=\"row\"| Germany\n|-\n\n! scope=\"row\"| Switzerland\n|-\n\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| United Kingdom\n| August 14, 2000<ref name=amazonuk1>{{cite web|title=Lucky [Single, Maxi] by Britney Spears|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Lucky-Britney-Spears/dp/B00004XP07|website=[[Amazon.com|Amazon.co.uk]]|accessdate=July 5, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n\n| August 22, 2000 (Part 2)<ref name=amazonuk2>{{cite web|title=Lucky Part 2 [Maxi] by Britney Spears|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Lucky-Part-2-Spears-Britney/dp/B0000DENMD|website=[[Amazon.com|Amazon.co.uk]]|accessdate=July 5, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|britney-spears|lucky}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Britney Spears}}\n{{Britney Spears singles}}\n{{good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lucky}}\n[[Category:2000 singles]]\n[[Category:Britney Spears songs]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Dave Meyers (director)]]\n[[Category:2000s ballads]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Austria]]\n[[Category:European Hot 100 Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Germany]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:UK Independent Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Jive Records singles]]\n[[Category:Pop ballads]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Max Martin]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Max Martin]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Rami Yacoub]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Alexander Kronlund]]\n[[Category:2000 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about loneliness]]\n[[Category:Songs about actors]]\n[[Category:Songs about fictional female characters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2000 single by Britney Spears}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Lucky\n| cover      = Britney Spears - Lucky.png\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Britney Spears]]\n| album      = [[Oops!... I Did It Again (album)|Oops!... I Did It Again]]\n| B-side     = Heart\n| released   = {{start date|2000|08|08}}\n| format     = {{flat list|\n*[[Cassette single]]\n*[[CD single]]\n*[[12-inch single|12\"]]\n}}\n| recorded   = November 1999\n| studio     =[[Cheiron Studios]] ([[Stockholm, Sweden|Stockholm]], [[Sweden]])\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Dance-pop]]|[[teen pop]]}}\n| length     ={{duration|m=3|s=24}}\n| label      = [[Jive Records|Jive]]\n| writer     = {{flat list|\n*[[Max Martin]]\n*[[Rami Yacoub]]\n*[[Alexander Kronlund]]\n}}\n| producer   = {{flat list|\n*Max Martin\n*Rami Yacoub\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Oops!... I Did It Again (song)|Oops!... I Did It Again]]\n| prev_year  = 2000\n| next_title = [[Stronger (Britney Spears song)|Stronger]]\n| next_year  = 2000\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|4vvBAONkYwI|\"Lucky\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Lucky'''\" is a song recorded by American singer [[Britney Spears]]. It was released on August 8, 2000 by [[Jive Records]] as the second single from her second studio album ''[[Oops!... I Did It Again (album)|Oops!... I Did It Again]]''. After meeting with producers [[Max Martin]] and [[Rami Yacoub]] in Sweden, the singer recorded several songs for the album, including \"Lucky\". The song tells a story about a famous movie star named Lucky, who, despite seemingly having it all \u2013 fame, wealth, beauty \u2013 is truly lonely and unhappy on the inside. It was praised by [[music journalism|music critics]], who considered its melody and rhythm as sweet and catchy, and noted the lyrics to be about Spears herself.\n\n\"Lucky\" achieved commercial success worldwide, peaking at number 1 in Austria, Germany, Sweden and Switzerland, while reaching the top 10 in several European countries. In the United Kingdom, the song peaked at number 5, and is Spears' tenth best-selling single in the country, having sold over 225,000 copies there. It also peaked at number 23 on the ''[[Billboard Hot 100]]'' in the United States. An accompanying music video was directed by [[Dave Meyers (director)|Dave Meyers]], and portrays Spears as herself and a melancholy movie star Lucky, who just wants to have some fun in life. Spears has performed \"Lucky\" in a number of live appearances and in two of her [[concert tour]]s.\n\n==Background and composition==\n{{Listen\n|pos=left\n|filename=LuckySample.ogg\n|title=\"Lucky\"\n|description=A 21-second sample of the song's chorus, which features Spears singing about a lonely pop star.<ref name=sheet/><ref name=canoe/>\n|format=[[Ogg]]\n}}\nIn 1999, Spears began work on her second studio album ''[[Oops!... I Did It Again (album)|Oops!... I Did It Again]]'' (2000), in Sweden and Switzerland.<ref name=mtvwork>{{cite web | last=Basham |first=David| title=Britney Spears Works On Next LP In Switzerland, Sweden | date=1999-11-19 | url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1434400/britney-spears-works-on-next-lp-switzerland-sweden.jhtml |publisher=[[MTV|MTV News]]. [[MTV Networks]]| accessdate=2009-07-29}}</ref><ref name=billmag>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iggEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA95 |title=Backstage At Awards |first=Melinda |last=Newman |date=1999-12-18|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=2011-01-19}}</ref> After meeting with [[Max Martin]] and [[Rami Yacoub]] in Sweden, Spears recorded several songs for the album,<ref name=mtvwork/> including \"Lucky\", which was co-written and co-produced by Martin and Rami, with additional co-writing from [[Alexander Kronlund]].<ref name=liner>{{cite AV media notes|title=Oops!... I Did It Again|others=Britney Spears|year=2000|publisher=[[Jive Records]]|type=Liner notes}}</ref> Upon returning to the United States, the singer revealed in an interview with [[MTV News]] that: \"I just got back from Sweden, and did half [of] the material [for ''Oops!''] over there. I was really, really happy with the material, but we had [such] limited time to get so much done. So I've just really been in the studio nonstop, which is cool, though.\"<ref name=mtvwork/> Spears recorded her vocals for the song, the first week of November 1999 at [[Cheiron Studios]] in [[Stockholm, Sweden]].<ref name=liner/> \"Lucky\" was released on August 8, 2000 as the second single from the album.<ref name=\"Austria\">{{cite web | url=http://austriancharts.at/showitem.asp?interpret=Britney+Spears&titel=Lucky&cat=s| title=Britney Spears \u2013 Lucky Austriancharts.at | publisher=[[\u00d63 Austria Top 40]]. Hung Medien | date=2004-04-08 | accessdate=2009-07-19}}</ref>\n\n\"Lucky\" is a song that lasts for three minutes and 24 seconds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/lucky-mw0000959920|title=Lucky \u2013 Britney Spears|publisher=[[Allmusic]]. [[Rovi Corporation]]|accessdate=2012-03-24}}</ref> According to the digital music sheet published at Musicnotes.com, the song is composed in the key of [[D-flat major|D{{music|flat}} major]] (but will later modulate to [[E-flat major|E{{music|flat}} major]] at the end of the bridge) and is set in the [[time signature]] of [[common time]] with a moderate [[tempo]] of 95 [[beats per minute]], while Spears' vocal range spans over an octave, from A{{music|flat}}<sub>3</sub> to E{{music|flat}}<sub>5</sub>. \"Lucky\" has a basic sequence of D{{music|flat}}\u2013B{{music|flat}}m\u2013G{{music|flat}}\u2013A{{music|flat}} as its [[chord progression]].<ref name=sheet>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtdVPE.asp?ppn=MN0037258|title=Britney Spears Lucky \u2013 Digital Sheet Music|publisher=Musicnotes.com. [[Universal Music Publishing Group]]|accessdate=2010-02-06|date=2000-08-21}}</ref> David Veitch of the ''[[Calgary Sun]]'' and Chuck Taylor of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' compared the song's rhythm to the ones of Spears' previous singles \"[[...Baby One More Time (song)|...Baby One More Time]]\" (1998) and \"[[Sometimes (Britney Spears song)|Sometimes]]\" (1999).<ref name=canoe>{{cite web|url=http://travel.canoe.ca/AllPop-SpearsBritney/cd_ooops1.html|title=Britney hits us one more time|last=Veitch|first=David|work=[[Calgary Sun]]|publisher=[[Sun Media]]|date=2000-05-13|accessdate=2011-06-11|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120719102417/http://travel.canoe.ca/AllPop-SpearsBritney/cd_ooops1.html|archivedate=2012-07-19}}</ref><ref name=billboardmag>{{cite journal |author=Taylor, Chuck |year=2000 |title=Britney Spears \u2013 Lucky: Single Spotlight |journal=Billboard |volume=112 |issue=32 |pages=108 |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |issn=0006-2510 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mBAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA26 |accessdate= 2011-05-04}}</ref> Lyrically, Spears tells \"a story about a girl named Lucky,\" who is a famous pop star that, despite having all that she wants, still feels lonely inside.<ref name=canoe/><ref name=billboardmag/> Veitch also commented that the lyrics actually refer to Spears' life.<ref name=canoe/>\n\n==Critical response==\n\"Lucky\" received general acclaim from [[music critics]]. A review by the ''[[NME]]'' staff said that \"Lucky\" is \"perhaps Britney's finest moment. The ultimate mallrat, bittersweet teenage symphony\".<ref name=nme/> They considered the song  Spears' version of \"[[Where Did It All Go Wrong?]]\" by English [[rock music|rock]] band [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]], and went to describe it as \"a heart-rending tale of life at the top of the teen pop tree, transformed into an anthem for dramatic, moody 12-year-old girls everywhere by Max Martin's scary talent for teenybop lyrics\".<ref name=nme/> However, it was noted that some of the lyrics \"sounds pretty heavy when you've just been dumped and Britney's [[Mickey Mouse Club]]-trained falsetto is reaching its peak\".<ref name=nme>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/britney-spears/2330|title=Oops!...I Did It Again - NME Review|work=[[NME]]|publisher=[[IPC Media]]|author=NME Staff|date=2000-05-29|accessdate=2010-12-19}}</ref> David Veitch of ''Calgary Sun'' called \"Lucky\" a \"sweetly melodic mid-tempo song\" and regarding the lyrics commented, \"We feel her pain\",<ref name=canoe/> ''Billboard'' magazine contributor Chuck Taylor praised \"Lucky\" and featured the song on the Spolight column of his Singles Review section. Taylor stated that: \"its contagious melody, bang-in-your-brain hook, the empathetic theme of a girl who's the world biggest superstar and yet feels all alone (hmm...) will make it an easy sell to top 40 radio and to her grand legion of dedicated fans\".<ref name=billboardmag/>\n\n''[[Rolling Stone]]'' called it \"one of her most bubbly tunes, but the lyrics about a miserable starlet suggest that she identified with the dark side of fame very early on in her career\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Readers\u2019 Poll: The Best Britney Spears Songs of All Time |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/readers-poll-the-best-britney-spears-songs-of-all-time-10323/ |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=December 7, 2011}}</ref> ''[[Gay Times]]''{{'}} Daniel Megarry felt that \"the bittersweet 'Lucky', which almost feels autobiographical, remains the ultimate throwback for 90s kids\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Megarry |first1=Daniel |title=We ranked every single Britney Spears album from worst to best |url=https://www.gaytimes.co.uk/culture/118767/we-ranked-every-single-britney-spears-album-from-worst-to-best/ |work=[[Gay Times]] |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=February 28, 2019}}</ref> The staff from ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' placed it at number 10 on their ranking of Spears's songs and said that \"given everything we know about Spears\u2019 past decade, it\u2019s hard not to hear 'Lucky' as a haunting premonition packaged in fairy dust\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Every Britney Spears song, ranked |url=https://ew.com/article/2016/09/01/every-britney-spears-song-ranked/ |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=September 1, 2016}}</ref> Erin Strecker, from ''Billboard'', called it \"one of the pop princess' great ballads\", and \"undoubtedly one of the high points of Britney Spears' career\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Strecker |first1=Erin |title=Britney Spears' 'Lucky' Turns 15: 5 Great Moments |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6633471/britney-spears-lucky-15-great-moments |work=Billboard |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=July 14, 2015}}</ref> Writing for ''[[Pink News]]'', Mayer Nissim called it a \"a \u201860s-infused self-reflective bit of pop\", but pointed out that \"there\u2019s a real sense of genuine emotion Spears gets across with some neat vocal flourishes\".<ref name=\"PinkNews\">{{cite web |last1=Nissim |first1=Mayer |title=Britney Spears \u2018\u2026Baby One More Time\u2019 at 20: All 42 Britney songs ranked |url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2018/10/18/britney-spears-singles-ranked/ |work=[[Pink News]] |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=October 18, 2018}}</ref> For Christopher Rosa from ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]'', it's Spears' fifth best song, as well as a \"perfect blend of the sweet-pop sound from her first record and lyrics that feel just a little more grown-up\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rosa |first1=Christopher |title=Britney Spears's 10 Best (and Worst) Songs of All Time |url=https://www.glamour.com/story/the-10-best-and-worst-britney-spears-songs-of-all-time |work=[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]] |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=November 17, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]''{{'}}s Alex Kristelis said that the song's \"bubblegum pop gloss disguises even its most devastating lyrics\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kristelis |first1=Alex |title=All 39 Britney Spears Singles Ranked from Totally Incredible to Totally Forgettable \u2014 LISTEN |url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/48071-all-39-britney-spears-singles-ranked-from-totally-incredible-to-totally-forgettable-listen |work=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=November 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\nIn the United States \"Lucky\" peaked at number 23 on [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and number nine on the [[Mainstream Top 40 (Pop Songs)|Top 40 Mainstream]] chart.<ref name=allmusic>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/britney-spears-mn0000628467/awards|title=Britney Spears USA Chart History|publisher=[[Allmusic]]. [[Rovi Corporation]]|accessdate=2011-01-30}}</ref> It also peaked at number 39 on the [[Hot Dance Singles Sales|Hot Dance Music/Maxi-Singles Sales]] component chart, and number 14 on [[Rhythmic Top 40]].<ref name=allmusic/> \"Lucky\" also achieved commercial success worldwide, reaching number one in Austria, Europe, Sweden and Switzerland,<ref name=swisschart/> while reaching the top ten in several European countries.<ref name=swisschart/> On the week of August 28, 2000 \"Lucky\" debuted at number 5 in the [[Official Charts Company]] from the United Kingdom, falling to number six in the following week.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/BRITNEY%20SPEARS/ | title=Britney Spears - Archive Chart|publisher=[[UK Singles Chart]]. [[Official Charts Company]] | date=2000-08-28 | accessdate=2009-07-17}}</ref> According to the Official Charts Company, it is her tenth best-selling single in the country, having sold over 225,000 copies there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/music/charts/official-uk-countdowns/britney-spears-official-top-20 |title=Britney Spears - Official Top 20 |publisher=[[MTV UK]]. [[MTV Networks]] |accessdate=2011-10-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101211124520/http://www.mtv.co.uk/music/charts/official-uk-countdowns/britney-spears-official-top-20 |archivedate=2010-12-11 }}</ref> In Australia, the song peaked at number three,<ref name=swisschart/> and was later certified Platinum by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA), for shipments of more than 70,000 units of the single.<ref name=auscert/> In Germany, the song reached number one on the [[Media Control Charts]], being certified Gold by the [[Bundesverband Musikindustrie]] (BVMI) for shipping over 250,000 units of the single.<ref name=gercert/>\n\n==Music video==\n[[File:Luckymusicvideo.jpg|right|thumb|Spears portraying melancholy movie star Lucky,<ref name=iwg/> as she wins her [[Academy Award for Best Actress]].|306x306px]]\n\nJive Records commissioned a music video for \"Lucky\" to be directed by [[Dave Meyers (director)|Dave Meyers]].<ref name=\"iwg\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1666198/britney-spears-i-wanna-go-paparazzi-video.jhtml|title=Britney Spears Vs. The Paparazzi: Best Music-Video Moments|last=Vena|first=Jocelyn|date=2011-06-22|accessdate=2012-03-24|publisher=[[MTV]]. [[MTV Networks]]}}</ref> It was shot on June 12 and 13, 2000 at the [[Red Studios Hollywood|Ren-Mar Studios]] in [[Hollywood]], [[California]]. According to Jocelyn Vena of [[MTV]], Spears portrays \"a melancholy movie star who wants nothing more than to have a little fun\".<ref name=\"iwg\" />\n\nThe video begins with Spears telling a story about a very famous [[Hollywood]] actress named Lucky. Lucky is seen wearing a pink nightgown behind the curtains, standing on her billboard with fluffy white cotton balls attached to the edges, inside her mansion and shots of her out on the balcony. As beautiful and rich as she is, on set she sits on the star-shape in the sky, as she is acting, she is looking quite distressed. After the first chorus, she goes to the hotel mansion to the flowers, then she leaves and sits down and gets a mirror. Next, Lucky opens the door to reveal a handsome man, who then takes her in his arms, as the director yells \"Cut! We've got it\". Lucky then walks off-set into the studio, replying to the director: \"Finally! We've done it fifty-million times!\" She then goes to have her hair and makeup done; with Spears standing unnoticed and very worried looking by her side. Lucky is then seen in a shiny gray evening gown at the [[Academy Awards]] accepting her [[Academy Award for Best Actress|award for Best Actress]]. Lucky looks happy as she accepts it and smiles at her fans but is soon revealed that this is not true happiness. She makes her way away from her screaming fans and back into her limo, where she unexpectedly finds an ornate hand mirror that was used on the film set. She looks back to the crowd to see who has left it and sees Spears leaning forward in the crowd. The limo drives away, leaving Spears behind on the red carpet. The video ends with Lucky crying herself to sleep, her make-up already stained on her face. The curtains close, ending the video.\n\nA ''Billboard'' staff reviewer noted that the story \"turned out to be less than pure fiction when the singer later went through personal problems in the very public eye.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/list/464875/britney-spears-20-biggest-billboard-hits|title=Britney Spears' 20 Biggest Billboard Hits|author=Billboard Staff|date=2011-12-02|accessdate=2012-03-24|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]}}</ref> Jarett Wieselman of the ''[[New York Post]]'' rated the video a C+ and stated that: \"Britney's first Hollywood cautionary tale video didn't seem quite as telling at the time, but with a little distance, the lyrics and concept seem so much sadder\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/britney_spears_music_video_report_4rrLUSeEJQRZusLm464f1K |title=Britney Spears' Music Video Report Card |last=Wieselman |first=Jarret |date=2011-02-15 |accessdate=2012-03-24 |work=[[New York Post]] |publisher=Paul Carlucci |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130706220031/http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/britney_spears_music_video_report_4rrLUSeEJQRZusLm464f1K |archivedate=2013-07-06 }}</ref> A writer of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' said that \"Lucky\" is best known for \"being the first Spears video to focus on what would become a recurring theme: her conflicted relationship to fame\".<ref name=rstone>{{cite journal|url=|title=The Complete Video Guide: \"Lucky\"|year=2009|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Jann Wenner]]|last=Reporter|first=Rolling Stone|issn=0035-791X}}</ref>\n\n== Live performances and cover version ==\n[[File:Taylor Swift - Speak Now tour 2011 02.jpg|left|thumb|[[Taylor Swift]] covered \"Lucky\" during her [[Speak Now Tour]], 2011.]]\n\nSpears performed \"Lucky\" for the first time during her [[Oops!... I Did It Again World Tour]] in Columbia, U.S.A at June 20, 2000. The performance of the song featured a [[navy]] theme.<ref name=pitch>{{cite news|url=http://www.pitch.com/kansascity/britney-spearsmikaila/Content?oid=2160897|title=Britney Spears/Mikaila|date=2000-07-20|accessdate=2010-01-20|last=Miller|first=Andrew|newspaper=[[The Pitch (newspaper)|The Pitch]]. [[Village Voice Media]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130722185904/http://www.pitch.com/kansascity/britney-spearsmikaila/Content?oid=2160897|archive-date=2013-07-22|url-status=dead}}</ref> The track was also on the [[Dream Within a Dream Tour]] (2001\u201302), where Spears emerged from the middle of a giant musical box on the stage as a [[ballerina]], to perform the song in a medley with \"[[Born to Make You Happy]]\" and \"[[Sometimes (Britney Spears song)|Sometimes]]\", right after the performance of \"[[Overprotected]]\".<ref name=livedesign>{{cite news|url=http://livedesignonline.com/mag/britneys_big_splash/index.html?smte=wr |title=Britney's Big Splash |date=2002-07-02 |accessdate=2010-02-04 |last=McHugh |first=Catherine |publisher=Live Design. [[Penton Media]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120610120736/http://livedesignonline.com/mag/britneys_big_splash/index.html?smte=wr |archivedate=2012-06-10 }}</ref><ref name=mtvreview>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1450487/britney-live-report-from-ohio.jhtml |title=Britney Goes Bald, Plays Tiny Dancer, Gets Caught In The Rain At Tour Kickoff |last=Reid |first=Shaheem |last2=Moss |first2=Corey |date=2001-11-02 |work=[[MTV]] |publisher=[[MTV Networks]] |accessdate=2010-01-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130621220417/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1450487/britney-live-report-from-ohio.jhtml |archivedate=2013-06-21 }}</ref> Spears also performed the song on several [[TV|television appearances]], including at the ''[[Top of the Pops|Top of the Pops Germany]]'' in 2000,<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Top of the Pops Germany |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5e9PZ9C5wDI |accessdate=2012-03-24 |credits=[[Johnnie Stewart]] |network=[[BBC One]] |station= |city= |airdate=2000-08-25|language=English}}</ref> and at ''[[The Today Show]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/slideshows/entertainment/slideshow/Britney-Spears-through-the-years-4911.php#photo-678818|title=Britney Spears through the years|date=2000-06-30|accessdate=2012-03-24|work=[[San Antonio Express-News]]|publisher=Thomas A. Stephenson}}</ref> \"Lucky\" was included on the setlist of the [[Britney: Piece of Me]], Spears' Las Vegas residency show (2013 - 2016).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://metro.co.uk/2013/12/22/britney-spears-releases-setlist-for-las-vegas-residency-piece-of-me-4240529 |title=Britney Spears releases setlist for Las Vegas residency Piece of Me|newspaper=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|date=December 22, 2013|accessdate=December 24, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://popcrush.com/britney-spears-piece-of-me-residency-revamp-opening-night-photos/|title= Britney Spears Kicks Off Remixed, Reimagined and Still Very Much Iconic 'Piece of Me' Residency in Las Vegas|last=Stern|first=Bradley|publisher=PopCrush. [[Townsquare Media]], Inc.|date=February 13, 2016|accessdate=February 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nCountry singer [[Taylor Swift]] performed the song on her [[Speak Now World Tour]] on September 20, 2011 located in [[Louisiana]], as a tribute to Spears.<ref name=pd/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/videos-taylor-swifts-coast-to-coast-cover-songs-20111116/lucky-in-bossier-city-0828097|title=Videos: Taylor Swift's Coast-to-Coast Cover Songs|date=2011-09-20|accessdate=2012-03-24|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Jann Wenner]]}}</ref> Wearing her signature lilac dress, Swift started to play the first chords of \"Lucky\" on her guitar, while singing, \"Early morning/She wakes up/With a knock, knock, knock on the {{sic|the}} door/It's time for makeup/Perfect smile/It's you they're all waiting for.\"<ref name=ts>{{cite web|url=http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2011/09/22/taylor-swift-britney-spears-lucky-cover/|title=Taylor Swift Covers Britney Spears' 'Lucky' (!!!!) (VIDEO)|date=2011-09-22|accessdate=2012-03-24|publisher=[[MTV]]. [[MTV Networks]]|first=Jenna Hally|last=Rubenstein|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111227181808/http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2011/09/22/taylor-swift-britney-spears-lucky-cover|archivedate=2011-12-27}}</ref> Scott Shetler of Pop Crush said that \"the crowd energy for the Britney cover didn't seem as high as when Swift covered [[Eminem]] in Detroit or [[Justin Bieber]] in Toronto.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://popcrush.com/taylor-swift-covers-britney-spears-lucky/|title=TAYLOR SWIFT COVERS BRITNEY SPEARS' 'LUCKY'|last=Shetler|first=Scott|date=2011-09-21|accessdate=2012-03-24|publisher=Pop Crush}}</ref> Jenna Hally Rubenstein of [[MTV]], however, praised the performance, and noted that the show's crowd gave a positive reaction to the cover, saying, \"though the video is sideways and features the amateur videographer's own personal sing-along, the excitement in her voice is a testament to Taylor's song choice. Or in other words, we can almost guarantee that every normal, living, breathing Louisiana-bred girl in attendance at Taylor's show is also obsessed with Britney Spears.\"<ref name=ts/> Becky Bain of [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] said that she had no doubts that Swift would cover a Spears song, but was surprised that the song Swift chose was \"Lucky\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://idolator.com/6023962/taylor-swift-covers-britney-spears-lucky-in-louisiana|title=Taylor Swift Covers Britney Spears' \"Lucky\" In Louisiana|last=Bain|first=Becky|date=2011-09-23|accessdate=2012-03-24|publisher=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]. [[Buzz Media]]}}</ref> PopDust writer Katherine St Asaph said that \"Lucky\" is \"one of the few Britney lyrics that could just as easily be written for/by Taylor and one of the few songs that wouldn\u2019t need massive re-arranging.\"<ref name=pd>{{cite web|url=http://popdust.com/2011/09/23/taylor-swift-britney-spears-lucky-cover/|last=St Asaph|first=Katherine|date=2011-09-23|accessdate=2012-03-24|publisher=PopDust|title=Taylor Swift Chooses Her Louisiana Britney Spears Cover Wisely}}</ref>\n\n== Track listings ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n*;European CD single\n#\"Lucky\" (Album Version)&nbsp;\u2014 3:24\n#\"Heart\"&nbsp;\u2014 3:00\n\n*;European CD maxi single\n#\"Lucky\" (Album Version)&nbsp;\u2014 3:24\n#\"Heart\"&nbsp;\u2014 3:00\n#\"Lucky\" ([[Jack D. Elliot]] Radio Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 3:26\n\n*;Australian CD maxi single (Part 1)\n#\"Lucky\" (Album Version)&nbsp;\u2014 3:24\n#\"Heart\"&nbsp;\u2014 3:00\n#\"Lucky\" (Jack D. Elliot Radio Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 3:26\n#\"[[Oops!... I Did It Again (song)|Oops!... I Did It Again]]\" (Jack D. Elliot Club Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 6:24\n\n*;Australian CD maxi single (Part 2)\n#\"Lucky\" (Album Version)&nbsp;\u2014 3:24\n#\"Oops!... I Did It Again\" ([[Rodney Jerkins]] Remix)&nbsp;\u2014 3:07\n#\"Oops!... I Did It Again\" (Ospina's Crossover Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 3:15\n#\"Lucky\" ([[Jason Nevins]] Mixshow Edit)&nbsp;\u2014 5:51\n#\"Lucky\" (Riprock and [[Alex Greggs|Alex G.]] Radio Edit)&nbsp;\u2014 3:58\n#\"Oops!... I Did It Again\" ([[Enhanced CD|Enhanced Video]])&nbsp;\u2014 4:12\n{{col-2}}\n*;Japanese CD maxi single\n#\"Lucky\" (Album Version)&nbsp;\u2014 3:24\n#\"Lucky\" (Jack D. Elliot Radio Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 3:26\n#\"Oops!... I Did It Again\" (Ospina's Crossover Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 3:15\n#\"Oops!... I Did It Again\" (Riprock 'n' Alex G. Oops! We Remixed Again! Radio Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 3:54\n\n*;Australian cassette single\n#\"Lucky\" (Album Version)&nbsp;\u2014 3:24\n#\"Lucky\" (Jack D. Elliot Radio Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 3:26\n#\"Oops!... I Did It Again\" (Jack D. Elliot Club Mix)&nbsp;\u2014 6:24\n\n*;European cassette single\n#\"Lucky\" (Album Version)&nbsp